Defining a Mean-Reversion Strategy (Bollinger Bands)¶

Mean Reversion: Financial Instrument are from time to time overbought / oversold and revert back to men prices.

Bollinger Bands: Consistes of a SMA (e.g. 30) and Upper and Lower Bands +- (2) Std Dev away from SMA.

In [11]:
#defining SMA and Standard Deviation of Bollinger Bands
SMA = 30
dev = 2

In [17]:
# making lower band of bollinger band which substrac SMA as middle line 
data['Lower'] = data['SMA'] - data['price'].rolling(SMA).std() * dev # lower band -2 std dev
In [18]:
## making upper band of bollinger band which adding SMA as middle line 
data['Upper'] = data['SMA'] + data['price'].rolling(SMA).std() * dev # lower band +2 std dev

#calculated distance
data['distance'] = data.price - data.SMA # helper column
In [45]:
#making position for oversold which we go long
#if price less than lower bound we asignt value of 1, otherwise asignt NaN
data['position'] = np.where(data.price < data.Lower, 1, np.nan) # oversold -> go long
In [47]:
#making position for overbought which we go short
#if price more than upper bound we asignt value of -1, otherwise it previous data asignment
data['position'] = np.where(data.price > data.Upper, -1, data['position'])#overbought -> go short
